CXU080110LB05A1M.title: Expenditures: Eggs by Size of Consumer Unit: Five People in Consumer Unit
CXU080110LB05A1M.notes:
Size refers to the number of persons whose usual place of residence at the time of the interview is in the sample unit.

A consumer unit comprises either: (1) all members of a particular household who are related by blood, marriage, adoption, or other legal arrangements; (2) a person living alone or sharing a household with others or living as a roomer in a private home or lodging house or in permanent living quarters in a hotel or motel, but who is financially independent; or (3) two or more persons living together who use their income to make joint expenditure decisions. Financial independence is determined by the three major expense categories: Housing, food, and other living expenses. To be considered financially independent, at least two of the three major expense categories have to be provided entirely, or in part, by the respondent.

For more details about the data or the survey, visit the FAQs (https://www.bls.gov/cex/csxfaqs.htm).

CXU080110LB1402M.title: Expenditures: Eggs by Highest Education: Less Than College Graduate: Total
CXU080110LB1402M.notes:
Highest education refers to the highest education level of any member in the consumer unit.

A consumer unit comprises either: (1) all members of a particular household who are related by blood, marriage, adoption, or other legal arrangements; (2) a person living alone or sharing a household with others or living as a roomer in a private home or lodging house or in permanent living quarters in a hotel or motel, but who is financially independent; or (3) two or more persons living together who use their income to make joint expenditure decisions. Financial independence is determined by the three major expense categories: Housing, food, and other living expenses. To be considered financially independent, at least two of the three major expense categories have to be provided entirely, or in part, by the respondent.

For more details about the data or the survey, visit the FAQs (https://www.bls.gov/cex/csxfaqs.htm).

CXU190904LB05A1M.title: Expenditures: Food Prepared on Out-of-Town Trips by Size of Consumer Unit: Five People in Consumer Unit
CXU190904LB05A1M.notes:
Size refers to the number of persons whose usual place of residence at the time of the interview is in the sample unit.

A consumer unit comprises either: (1) all members of a particular household who are related by blood, marriage, adoption, or other legal arrangements; (2) a person living alone or sharing a household with others or living as a roomer in a private home or lodging house or in permanent living quarters in a hotel or motel, but who is financially independent; or (3) two or more persons living together who use their income to make joint expenditure decisions. Financial independence is determined by the three major expense categories: Housing, food, and other living expenses. To be considered financially independent, at least two of the three major expense categories have to be provided entirely, or in part, by the respondent.

For more details about the data or the survey, visit the FAQs (https://www.bls.gov/cex/csxfaqs.htm).

CXU190904LB0502M.title: Expenditures: Food Prepared on Out-of-Town Trips by Size of Consumer Unit: One Person Consumer Unit
CXU190904LB0502M.notes:
Size refers to the number of persons whose usual place of residence at the time of the interview is in the sample unit.

A consumer unit comprises either: (1) all members of a particular household who are related by blood, marriage, adoption, or other legal arrangements; (2) a person living alone or sharing a household with others or living as a roomer in a private home or lodging house or in permanent living quarters in a hotel or motel, but who is financially independent; or (3) two or more persons living together who use their income to make joint expenditure decisions. Financial independence is determined by the three major expense categories: Housing, food, and other living expenses. To be considered financially independent, at least two of the three major expense categories have to be provided entirely, or in part, by the respondent.

For more details about the data or the survey, visit the FAQs (https://www.bls.gov/cex/csxfaqs.htm).

CXU220211LB0502M.title: Expenditures: Property Taxes by Size of Consumer Unit: One Person Consumer Unit
CXU220211LB0502M.notes:
Size refers to the number of persons whose usual place of residence at the time of the interview is in the sample unit.

A consumer unit comprises either: (1) all members of a particular household who are related by blood, marriage, adoption, or other legal arrangements; (2) a person living alone or sharing a household with others or living as a roomer in a private home or lodging house or in permanent living quarters in a hotel or motel, but who is financially independent; or (3) two or more persons living together who use their income to make joint expenditure decisions. Financial independence is determined by the three major expense categories: Housing, food, and other living expenses. To be considered financially independent, at least two of the three major expense categories have to be provided entirely, or in part, by the respondent.

For more details about the data or the survey, visit the FAQs (https://www.bls.gov/cex/csxfaqs.htm).

CXU220211LB0602M.title: Expenditures: Property Taxes by Composition of Consumer Unit: Total Married Couple Consumer Units
CXU220211LB0602M.notes:

Stepchildren and adopted children are included with the reference person's own children. 
The reference person is the first member mentioned by the respondent when asked to "Start with the name of the person or one of the persons who owns or rents the home." It is with respect to this person that the relationship of the other consumer unit members is determined.

CXU220211LB1402M.title: Expenditures: Property Taxes by Highest Education: Less Than College Graduate: Total
CXU220211LB1402M.notes:
Highest education refers to the highest education level of any member in the consumer unit.

A consumer unit comprises either: (1) all members of a particular household who are related by blood, marriage, adoption, or other legal arrangements; (2) a person living alone or sharing a household with others or living as a roomer in a private home or lodging house or in permanent living quarters in a hotel or motel, but who is financially independent; or (3) two or more persons living together who use their income to make joint expenditure decisions. Financial independence is determined by the three major expense categories: Housing, food, and other living expenses. To be considered financially independent, at least two of the three major expense categories have to be provided entirely, or in part, by the respondent.

For more details about the data or the survey, visit the FAQs (https://www.bls.gov/cex/csxfaqs.htm).

CXU270102LB0502M.title: Expenditures: Cellular Phone Service by Size of Consumer Unit: One Person Consumer Unit
CXU270102LB0502M.notes:
Size refers to the number of persons whose usual place of residence at the time of the interview is in the sample unit.

A consumer unit comprises either: (1) all members of a particular household who are related by blood, marriage, adoption, or other legal arrangements; (2) a person living alone or sharing a household with others or living as a roomer in a private home or lodging house or in permanent living quarters in a hotel or motel, but who is financially independent; or (3) two or more persons living together who use their income to make joint expenditure decisions. Financial independence is determined by the three major expense categories: Housing, food, and other living expenses. To be considered financially independent, at least two of the three major expense categories have to be provided entirely, or in part, by the respondent.

For more details about the data or the survey, visit the FAQs (https://www.bls.gov/cex/csxfaqs.htm).

Composition of consumer unit refers to the classification of interviewed families according to: (1) relationship of other family members to the reference person; (2) age of the children of the reference person; and (3) combination of relationship to the reference person and age of the children. Stepchildren and adopted children are included with the reference person's own children. 
The reference person is the first member mentioned by the respondent when asked to "Start with the name of the person or one of the persons who owns or rents the home." It is with respect to this person that the relationship of the other consumer unit members is determined.

For more details about the data or the survey, visit the FAQs (https://www.bls.gov/cex/csxfaqs.htm).

CXU270102LB1402M.title: Expenditures: Cellular Phone Service by Highest Education: Less Than College Graduate: Total
CXU270102LB1402M.notes:
Highest education refers to the highest education level of any member in the consumer unit.

A consumer unit comprises either: (1) all members of a particular household who are related by blood, marriage, adoption, or other legal arrangements; (2) a person living alone or sharing a household with others or living as a roomer in a private home or lodging house or in permanent living quarters in a hotel or motel, but who is financially independent; or (3) two or more persons living together who use their income to make joint expenditure decisions. Financial independence is determined by the three major expense categories: Housing, food, and other living expenses. To be considered financially independent, at least two of the three major expense categories have to be provided entirely, or in part, by the respondent.

For more details about the data or the survey, visit the FAQs (https://www.bls.gov/cex/csxfaqs.htm).

CXU500110LB1402M.title: Expenditures: Vehicle Insurance by Highest Education: Less Than College Graduate: Total
CXU500110LB1402M.notes:
Highest education refers to the highest education level of any member in the consumer unit.

A consumer unit comprises either: (1) all members of a particular household who are related by blood, marriage, adoption, or other legal arrangements; (2) a person living alone or sharing a household with others or living as a roomer in a private home or lodging house or in permanent living quarters in a hotel or motel, but who is financially independent; or (3) two or more persons living together who use their income to make joint expenditure decisions. Financial independence is determined by the three major expense categories: Housing, food, and other living expenses. To be considered financially independent, at least two of the three major expense categories have to be provided entirely, or in part, by the respondent.

For more details about the data or the survey, visit the FAQs (https://www.bls.gov/cex/csxfaqs.htm).

CXU800721LB0502M.title: Other Financial Information: Estimated Market Value of Owned Home by Size of Consumer Unit: One Person Consumer Unit
CXU800721LB0502M.notes:
Size refers to the number of persons whose usual place of residence at the time of the interview is in the sample unit.

A consumer unit comprises either: (1) all members of a particular household who are related by blood, marriage, adoption, or other legal arrangements; (2) a person living alone or sharing a household with others or living as a roomer in a private home or lodging house or in permanent living quarters in a hotel or motel, but who is financially independent; or (3) two or more persons living together who use their income to make joint expenditure decisions. Financial independence is determined by the three major expense categories: Housing, food, and other living expenses. To be considered financially independent, at least two of the three major expense categories have to be provided entirely, or in part, by the respondent.

For more details about the data or the survey, visit the FAQs (https://www.bls.gov/cex/csxfaqs.htm).

CXU800721LB1402M.title: Other Financial Information: Estimated Market Value of Owned Home by Highest Education: Less Than College Graduate: Total
CXU800721LB1402M.notes:
Highest education refers to the highest education level of any member in the consumer unit.

A consumer unit comprises either: (1) all members of a particular household who are related by blood, marriage, adoption, or other legal arrangements; (2) a person living alone or sharing a household with others or living as a roomer in a private home or lodging house or in permanent living quarters in a hotel or motel, but who is financially independent; or (3) two or more persons living together who use their income to make joint expenditure decisions. Financial independence is determined by the three major expense categories: Housing, food, and other living expenses. To be considered financially independent, at least two of the three major expense categories have to be provided entirely, or in part, by the respondent.

For more details about the data or the survey, visit the FAQs (https://www.bls.gov/cex/csxfaqs.htm).

CXU900000LB0502M.title: Income Before Taxes: Wages and Salaries by Size of Consumer Unit: One Person Consumer Unit
CXU900000LB0502M.notes:
Size refers to the number of persons whose usual place of residence at the time of the interview is in the sample unit.

A consumer unit comprises either: (1) all members of a particular household who are related by blood, marriage, adoption, or other legal arrangements; (2) a person living alone or sharing a household with others or living as a roomer in a private home or lodging house or in permanent living quarters in a hotel or motel, but who is financially independent; or (3) two or more persons living together who use their income to make joint expenditure decisions. Financial independence is determined by the three major expense categories: Housing, food, and other living expenses. To be considered financially independent, at least two of the three major expense categories have to be provided entirely, or in part, by the respondent.

For more details about the data or the survey, visit the FAQs (https://www.bls.gov/cex/csxfaqs.htm).

CXU900000LB0602M.notes:

CXU900000LB1402M.title: Income Before Taxes: Wages and Salaries by Highest Education: Less Than College Graduate: Total
CXU900000LB1402M.notes:
Highest education refers to the highest education level of any member in the consumer unit.

A consumer unit comprises either: (1) all members of a particular household who are related by blood, marriage, adoption, or other legal arrangements; (2) a person living alone or sharing a household with others or living as a roomer in a private home or lodging house or in permanent living quarters in a hotel or motel, but who is financially independent; or (3) two or more persons living together who use their income to make joint expenditure decisions. Financial independence is determined by the three major expense categories: Housing, food, and other living expenses. To be considered financially independent, at least two of the three major expense categories have to be provided entirely, or in part, by the respondent.

For more details about the data or the survey, visit the FAQs (https://www.bls.gov/cex/csxfaqs.htm).

CXU910050LB05A1M.title: Other Financial Information: Estimated Monthly Rental Value of Owned Home by Size of Consumer Unit: Five People in Consumer Unit
CXU910050LB05A1M.notes:
Size refers to the number of persons whose usual place of residence at the time of the interview is in the sample unit.

A consumer unit comprises either: (1) all members of a particular household who are related by blood, marriage, adoption, or other legal arrangements; (2) a person living alone or sharing a household with others or living as a roomer in a private home or lodging house or in permanent living quarters in a hotel or motel, but who is financially independent; or (3) two or more persons living together who use their income to make joint expenditure decisions. Financial independence is determined by the three major expense categories: Housing, food, and other living expenses. To be considered financially independent, at least two of the three major expense categories have to be provided entirely, or in part, by the respondent.

For more details about the data or the survey, visit the FAQs (https://www.bls.gov/cex/csxfaqs.htm).
